From: nvidia-driver-injector <noreply@example.invalid>
Date: 2026-05-12
Subject: [PATCH 0002/0007] tb-egpu: clear AER UncMask at probe

Cluster P5 of the P1-P6 refactor. Standalone — no dependencies on
other clusters. Independent of NVreg_TbEgpuRecoverEnable; runs at
probe whenever the eGPU is enumerated.

What this changes
-----------------

At PCI probe time, clear the Uncorrectable Error Mask register on the
NVIDIA GPU's AER extended capability. Without this, the Linux PCI core
+ AORUS BIOS leave UncMask bit 22 (Uncorrectable Internal Error) set,
which causes Uncorrectable Internal Errors to be SILENTLY DOWNGRADED
to Advisory Non-Fatal per PCIe r6 §6.2.3.2: UncStatus stays clear,
Header Log is not captured, pci_error_handlers are NOT called.

After this patch, those errors take the standard AER recovery path
instead: status latched, Header Log populated, pcie_err_handlers fire.
On hosts that enable Lever M-recover (P2), the in-driver state machine
then dispatches slot_reset/resume — but that's a separate concern;
this patch is useful even with M-recover disabled because it makes
the errors visible in dmesg + lspci AER decode.

How we discovered the default was wrong
---------------------------------------

We observed every Gen3 probe-end firing Cor=0x2000 with no Uncor capture
and no recovery hook. Comparing AER register state against the Windows
nvlddmkm driver on the same hardware (2026-05-07) showed Windows runs
with UncMask = 0. The justification stands on its own merits — standard
PCIe AER recovery requires UncStatus to be latched, which the mask
demotion path bypasses — but the cross-OS comparison was how the
regression was found.

Implementation
--------------

New translation unit kernel-open/nvidia/nv-tb-egpu-aer.{c,h} exposing
a single function:

    int tb_egpu_aer_clear_uncor_mask(struct pci_dev *pdev);

Called once from nv_pci_probe, right after the SR-IOV early-exit and
before the rest of probe begins. SR-IOV virtual functions don't have
the AER ext-cap and don't reach the call.

Gated by NVreg_TbEgpuAerUncMaskClear (default 1). Bound-checks the
ext-cap offset against [0x100, 0x1000) to refuse broken-hardware values.
Read-then-write-if-needed pattern; logs old/new mask at info level when
the mask was non-zero, debug level when already zero, warn on
config-space errors. No mutation when the parameter is 0.

Why a separate TU
-----------------

The legacy patch 0022 inlined the AER mask manipulation inside Lever
M-recover's init function with an explicit comment that the coupling
was wrong but expedient. The separate TU makes the independence real:
P5 has no dependency on P2's state machine, can be tested standalone,
and stands as a reasonable upstream-candidate change in isolation.

